title.narrative: EDY- Kenya Youth Employment and Skills (K-YES) Program

description.narrative: (Kenya): The Kenya Youth Employment and Skills program (K-YES) aims to enhance employment opportunities for young high school dropouts through vocational skills training that lead to either wage or self-employment. Specific activities include: support to vocational training centers across nine counties, business skills training complemented with improved access to financial services, and opportunities for small agribusiness enterprise development along key value chains. In FY 2018, K-YES will provide 4,000 youth with technical and soft skills for wage and self-employment. To promote sustainability, K-YES brings county government and the local private sector together to form a compact, solidifying, local ownership over the process of connecting vocational training with local employment opportunities. This structure is geared towards a sustainable solution concerning the youth bulge in Kenya as it moves the country long it's self-reliance journey, where the K-YES beneficiaries will be part of Kenya's development solutions in the future. Furthermore, increased economic and employment opportunities for youth reduces their susceptibility for recruitment into violent and extremist groups and increases the supply of skilled labor for the private sector. K-YES activities that train youth to participate in Kenya's economic development are aligned with the Department of State and USAID Joint Strategic Plan's (JSP) objective to "promote healthy, educated, and productive populations in partner countries to drive inclusive and sustainable development, open new markets, and support U.S. prosperity and security objectives."
